 from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ramsey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish (Antrim): habitational name from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire, now part of Cambridgeshire), from Old English <i>hramsa</i> ‘wild garlic’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’. Alternatively, the name may also arise from Ramsey (Essex), probably from the same etymology as the Huntingdonshire placename. However, this is unlikely to be the source of the Scottish surname. This form of the surname is also common in Ireland, where it is probably in most if not all cases an altered form of Scottish   Ramsay  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ramsay","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant (the usual spelling in Scotland) of   Ramsey  . The Scottish Ramsays derive from Simund <i>de Ramesie</i>, recorded before 1175, who went to Scotland from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice De Ramsey was born in 1392, in Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England, her father, Sir Ralph Ramsay Sheriff of Suffolk, was 22 and her mother, Alice de Walsingham, was 18. She had at least 1 daughter with Thomas Charles. She died in 1451, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 59, and was buried in Astley, Lancashire, England."},"et":{"1392–1451":"1392–1451","1396–1460":"1396–1460","1405–1464":"1405–1464","1382–1412":"1382–1412","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1370–1464":"1370–1464","1374–1426":"1374–1426","1451":"1451","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","1426":"1426","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1464":"1464","Between 9 January 1392 and 8 January 1393":"9. jaanuar 1392 kuni 8. jaanuar 1393","1405":"1405","Great Bealings, Suffolk, England":"Great Bealings, Suffolk, England","Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England":"Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Kettleborough, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Astley St. Stephen, Lancashire, England":"Astley, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1392–1451":"1392–1451","1396–1460":"1396–1460","1405–1464":"1405–1464","1382–1412":"1382–1412","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1370–1464":"1370–1464","1374–1426":"1374–1426","1451":"1451","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","1426":"1426","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1464":"1464","Between 9 January 1392 and 8 January 1393":"vuodesta 9. tammikuuta 1392 vuoteen 8. tammikuuta 1393","1405":"1405","Great Bealings, Suffolk, England":"Great Bealings, Suffolk, England","Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England":"Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Kettleborough, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Astley St. Stephen, Lancashire, England":"Astley, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1392–1451":"1392–1451","1396–1460":"1396–1460","1405–1464":"1405–1464","1382–1412":"1382–1412","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1370–1464":"1370–1464","1374–1426":"1374–1426","1451":"1451","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1392":"139